/PG646/XX/PR

/KAHOSHANOT / PRAYERS FOR REDEMPTION/PR

/ITDuring Sukkot, the /MDHoshanot/XX are recited as part of the Torah service (see page 392). A
Torah scroll is brought to the lectern, and the reader chants. Except on Shabbat, the /MDlulav/XX
and /MDetrog/XX are held. On the first day of Sukkot, continue below. On Shabbat of Sukkot,
turn to page 650./PR

/PR

Hosha na!/PR

For your sake, our God, Hosha na!/PR

For your sake, our Creator, Hosha na!/PR

For your sake, our Redeemer, Hosha na!/PR

For your sake, our Teacher, Hosha na!/PR

/ITA procession is formed around the synagogue. The /MDlulav/XX and /MDetrog/XX are carried and the
following is chanted:/PR

/PR

For the sake of your All-embracing truth,/PR

for the sake of your Binding covenant,/PR

for the sake of your Greatness and your beauty,/PR

for the sake of your Divine decree,/PR

for the sake of your Heavenly splendor,/PR

for the sake of your Wise assembly,/PR

for the sake of your Sign and remembrance,/PR

for the sake of your Heavenly love,/PR

for the sake of your Timeless good,/PI/PR

/SCN/XXOTE/XX. An alphabetical acrostic occurs in the Hebrew of ך ן / for
the sake of your All-embracing truth, signifying the all-encompassing
divine presence.The English translation also contains an acrostic based on
the Hebrew alphabet.    /SC/XXR.S./XX/PR

/PR

